photo.title: Armorial bookplate of Le Gendre Pierce Starkie (1796-1819)
photo.description: Likely Le Gendre Pierce Starkie (1796-1819) of Huntroyd (Lancashire, United Kingdom) or perhaps his father of the same name (1760-1807). This website on the Starkie family gives "Le Gendre Piers Starkie" for the elder (1760-1807) and "Le Gendre Pierce Starkie" for the younger (1796-1819). The book in which this plate appears (Abraham and Gottfried Bucholzer's Index Chronologicus) was purchased by the Penn Libraries in 1962, the same year the library of Guy Piers Le Gendre Starkie was sold by Sotheby's. At this sale the Huntington Library purchased a 14th-century Mariale ms. with the "[b]ookplate of Le Gendre Pierce Starkie (b. 1796)" that is known to have been owned by Richard Wroe. Penn's Index Chronologicus has Richard Wroe's autograph on the title leaf as well as this Starkie bookplate. This plate is therefore most likely that of Starkie the younger. Penn Libraries call number: GC55 B8537 584c 1599 All images from this book

photo.title: Woodcut arms probably to be associated with the principality of Braunschweig-Lüneburg-Wolffenbüttel; used by Conrad Horn of Wolfenbüttel
photo.description: Woodcut arms probably to be associated with the principality of Braunschweig-Lüneburg-Wolffenbüttel. The work in which it appears contains a "Fürstliche Braunschweigische Hoffgerichts Ordnung"; various elements of the whole are present in the arms of Braunschweig-Lüneburg, and Wolffenbüttel. The initials "G.V.M.G." at head stand for "Gottes Versehen muss geschehen" ("God's providence must happen"), a motto which appears on (among other things) the coinage of Julius, Duke of Braunschweig-Lüneburg (1528-1589). Cf. this coin from Julius's reign, which includes the above arms on its reverse. Used by Conrad Horn of Wolfenbüttel. Blazon for the crest: Out of a Ducal Coronet a pillar proper, the top adorned with a Coronet and Plume of three Peacock’s Feathyers proper, charged with a Star argent; on either side of the Pillar, out of the Coronet, a Sickle argent, handles gules, the backs adorned with small tufts of Peacocks Feathers, and between the sickles before the pillar a Horse current argent. photo.title: Austin Lamont (1905-1969)
photo.description: Probably Austin Lamont (1905-1969), son of Thomas W. Lamont, banker at JP Morgan after whom Harvard's Lamont Library is named. According to this article in Anesthesiology, Austin Lamont was "originally planning to study classic Latin and Greek at the New College, Oxford University, England, [but] he changed his mind while still on the steamship headed for Europe." He instead studied science and became a doctor and professor of anesthesiology at the University of Pennsylvania School of Medicine (1947-mid1960s). Austin and his 2nd wife Bodine were Philadelphia elites and associated with other prominent Philadelphians Carl and Laura Zigrosser. Carl Zigrosser was a prints curator at the Philadelphia Museum of Art and member of the Print Club (Philadelphia). A finding aid to Zigrosser's papers is available here. Other examples of Austin Lamont's autograph. Penn Libraries call number: EC7 Ad214 713c 1756

photo.title: Book label of John Penington & Son bookshop at 127 S. 7th Street in Philadelphia, PA
photo.description: Book label of John Penington & Son bookshop at 127 S. 7th Street in Philadelphia, PA. The Peningtons arrived in Pennsylvania in 1698 and were a leading and active Quaker family in Philadelphia business and politics. John Penington (1799-1867‏) and his son, Edward Penington, ran the book shop and specialized in rare and foreign books. John's father, Edward, was a bibliophile with a large personal library of over 6,000 volumes and was a prominent businessman in the city as a sugar refiner and merchant. Cf. the Penington Family Papers at the Historical Society of Pennsylvania. One of 34 woodcut illustrations, each hand-colored, of the coats of arms of the Hochmeister or Grand Masters of the Teutonic Knights, a German Catholic military (and initially hospitaller) order founded in the 12th century. The Teutonic Knights ruled Prussia (the subject of the volume in which these illustrations appear) from the 13th century until 1525 when their Hochmeister Albrecht von Brandenburg-Ansbach converted to Lutheranism, secularized the territory and became the first Duke of Prussia. Established heading: Teutonic Knights Established heading: Osterberger, Georg, ‡d d. ca. 1602 Penn Libraries call number: GC55 A100 584k All images from this book
